{"ts": "2026-06-09T17:58:23.380976+00:00", "update": {"tools": {"messages": [{"type": "tool", "data": {"content": [{"type": "text", "text": "| MCP:Lp806v | successfully downloaded text file (SHA: 890470cbcd8b22c382d09c9d7ffd222ed613ce36)", "id": "lc_06016498-59b3-4330-9cf4-8ccf2d673e56"}, {"type": "text", "text": "| MCP:Lp806v | #!/usr/bin/env bash\n| MCP:Lp806v | # Apply all SQL files under migrations/ to the running pgdev container.\n| MCP:Lp806v | # Order: filename glob, lexicographic.\n| MCP:Lp806v | set -euo pipefail\n| MCP:Lp806v | \n| MCP:Lp806v | CONTAINER=\"${PGDEV_CONTAINER:-pgdev_db}\"\n| MCP:Lp806v | DB_USER=\"${POSTGRES_USER:-app}\"\n| MCP:Lp806v | DB_NAME=\"${POSTGRES_DB:-app}\"\n| MCP:Lp806v | \n| MCP:Lp806v | # Note: relies on shell glob expansion ordering, not on `find`.\n| MCP:Lp806v | # Tested on bash and zsh with default LC_COLLATE.\n| MCP:Lp806v | for f in migrations/*.sql; do\n| MCP:Lp806v |     echo \"Applying $f\"\n| MCP:Lp806v |     docker exec -i \"$CONTAINER\" psql -U \"$DB_USER\" -d \"$DB_NAME\" < \"$f\"\n| MCP:Lp806v | done", "id": "lc_6693964f-0ab0-490c-be7c-92b24e7b384e"}], "additional_kwargs": {}, "response_metadata": {}, "type": "tool", "name": "get_file_contents", "id": "6a51ab97-3c0e-4529-89e9-44c298b56d94", "tool_call_id": "call_b3716ac3d19b44e69ae31d3a", "artifact": null, "status": "success"}}]}}}
{"ts": "2026-06-09T17:58:38.430945+00:00", "update": {"model": {"messages": [{"type": "ai", "data": {"content": "Here's a walkthrough of the database migrations in this repository, in the order they would be applied.\n\n---\n\n### How migrations are applied\n\nThe migration runner is `scripts/apply_migrations.sh`. It globs `migrations/*.sql` and applies each file in **lexicographic (filename) order** via `psql` against the running PostgreSQL container. So the `NNN_` prefix on each filename is what controls the ordering.\n\n---\n\n### Migration 1 — `001_create_users.sql`\n\n```sql\nCREATE TABLE users (\n    id           BIGSERIAL PRIMARY KEY,\n    email        TEXT UNIQUE NOT NULL,\n    display_name TEXT,\n    created_at   TIMESTAMPTZ NOT NULL DEFAULT now()\n);\n```\n\n**What it does:** Creates the `users` table — the foundational entity. Each user gets an auto-incrementing 64-bit `id`, a unique `email`, an optional `display_name`, and an automatic `created_at` timestamp.\n\n---\n\n### Migration 2 — `002_create_sessions.sql`\n\n```sql\nCREATE TABLE sessions (\n    id          UUID PRIMARY KEY,\n    user_id     BIGINT NOT NULL REFERENCES users(id) ON DELETE CASCADE,\n    issued_at   TIMESTAMPTZ NOT NULL DEFAULT now(),\n    expires_at  TIMESTAMPTZ NOT NULL\n);\n```\n\n**What it does:** Creates the `sessions` table for tracking user login sessions. Each session is identified by a UUID primary key and has a foreign key `user_id` pointing to `users(id)`. The `ON DELETE CASCADE` means if a user is deleted, all their sessions are automatically removed. `issued_at` is set automatically and `expires_at` is required (for session expiry logic).\n\n---\n\n### Migration 3 — `003_add_session_index.sql`\n\n```sql\nCREATE INDEX idx_sessions_user_id ON sessions(user_id);\n```\n\n**What it does:** Adds a B-tree index on the `user_id` column of the `sessions` table. This speeds up lookups that filter or join on \"give me all sessions for a given user\" — a common query pattern for authentication flows.\n\n---\n\n### Summary\n\n| Order | File | Purpose |\n|-------|------|---------|\n| 1 | `001_create_users.sql` | Creates the `users` table (id, email, display_name, created_at) |\n| 2 | `002_create_sessions.sql` | Creates the `sessions` table with a cascading FK to `users` |\n| 3 | `003_add_session_index.sql` | Adds an index on `sessions.user_id` for query performance |\n\nThe schema is minimal and focused: a basic user account model with session tracking — essentially a starter authentication scaffold backed by PostgreSQL 16.", "additional_kwargs": {"refusal": null}, "response_metadata": {"token_usage": {"completion_tokens": 591, "prompt_tokens": 8562, "total_tokens": 9153, "completion_tokens_details": {"accepted_prediction_tokens": null, "audio_tokens": null, "reasoning_tokens": 15, "rejected_prediction_tokens": null}, "prompt_tokens_details": {"audio_tokens": null, "cached_tokens": 8128}}, "model_provider": "openai", "model_name": "mimo-v2.5-pro", "system_fingerprint": null, "id": "50176ebca4bc4e738023f26e0dbdc99f", "finish_reason": "stop", "logprobs": null}, "type": "ai", "name": null, "id": "lc_run--019ead89-1795-7e12-9e33-63d9c03a2874-0", "tool_calls": [], "invalid_tool_calls": [], "usage_metadata": {"input_tokens": 8562, "output_tokens": 591, "total_tokens": 9153, "input_token_details": {"cache_read": 8128}, "output_token_details": {"reasoning": 15}}}}]}}}
{"kind": "token_usage", "ts": "2026-06-09T17:58:38.433017+00:00", "usage": {"input_tokens": 47577, "output_tokens": 1410, "total_tokens": 48987, "calls": 10}}
